{"bio": {"type": "/type/text", "value": "Melissa Scott is a science fiction and fantasy author noted for her science fiction novels featuring LGBT characters and elaborate settings. Scott studied history at Harvard College and Brandeis University, and earned her PhD. in comparative history. She published her first novel in 1984, and has since written some two dozen science fiction and fantasy works, including three co-authored with her life-partner, Lisa Barnett. Scott lived with Lisa, in Portsmouth, New Hampshire for 27 years, until the latter's death of breast cancer on May 2, 2006."}, "name": "Melissa Scott", "created": {"type": "/type/datetime", "value": "2008-04-01T03:28:50.625462"}, "personal_name": "Melissa Scott", "last_modified": {"type": "/type/datetime", "value": "2017-03-31T09:31:15.804079"}, "latest_revision": 4, "key": "/authors/OL193060A", "birth_date": "1960", "remote_ids": {"viaf": "11452411", "wikidata": "Q1919410"}, "type": {"key": "/type/author"}, "revision": 4}

{"bio": {"type": "/type/text", "value": "Rudy Rucker is a writer and a mathematician who worked for twenty years as a Silicon Valley computer science professor, and published a number of software packages.

Rucker is regarded as contemporary master of science-fiction, and received the Philip K. Dick award twice. His thirty published books include both novels and non-fiction books on the fourth dimension, infinity, and the meaning of computation.

A founder of the cyberpunk school of science-fiction, Rucker also writes SF in a realistic style known as transrealism. His 2006 Mathematicians in Love was an example of a transreal novel. His early cyberpunk four-book series was republished in 2010 as The Ware Tetralogy.

Rucker’s 2007 novel, Postsingular was something of a return to the cyberpunk style, as was the 2009 sequel, Hylozoic, in which every object on Earth comes to life. Rucker’s autobiography, , appeared in 2011. Recent novels include Jim and the Flims, Turing & Burroughs, and The Big Aha.

{"website": "http://www.harryharrison.com/", "bio": "Harry Max Harrison was born Henry Maxwell Dempsey in Stamford, Connecticut. He moved with his family to New York early in his childhood. On his 18th birthday, having graduated from high school, he was drafted into the U.S. Army Air Corps, and serves as an armourer, gunnery instructor, truck driver, and military police officer. When the war ended, he became an art student at both the Hunter College in New York City and the Cartoonists and Illustrators School. Upon graduation, he became a freelance graphic artist, providing illustrations for book covers, magazines, and comic books such as Weird Fantasy and Weird Science. He also began contributing articles to these magazines. In 1952, he moved into editing pulp magazines such as Amazing Stories and Fantastic. In 1954 he married, and their first child was born in 1955. In 1956 he became a full-time writer, and began working on his first book in addition to writing for other publications such as The Saint syndicated comic strips. Over the next decade he and his family moved to several places, including Mexico, England, Italy, back to New York for the birth of their second child in 1959, to Denmark for seven years, back to England in 1965, San Diego in 1967, and finally Ireland in 1975 where they settled. Harrison produced over 60 books, occasionally in collaboration with other well-known writers such as Gordon R. {"bio": {"type": "/type/text", "value": "Professor David A. McAllester received his B.S., M.S., and Ph.D. degrees from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1978, 1979, and 1987 respectively. After graduating, he taught at Cornell University for one year. In 1988 he moved to MIT. In 1995 he became a member of technical staff at AT&T Labs-Research, where he stayed until 2002. In 1997 he became a fellow of the American Association of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI). He is currently a professor at the Toyota Technological Institute at Chicago.\r\n\r\nMcAllester's research interests include machine learning theory, programming language theory, automated reasoning, AI planning, and computational linguistics."}, "name": "David A. {"bio": {"type": "/type/text", "value": "David J. Hagberg (born in Duluth, Minnesota) is an American novelist best known for his techno-thrillers featuring super-spy Kirk McGarvey. It is said that in his novel \"Joshua's Hammer\", for example, written in 2000, Hagberg gives a chilling account of a mega-terrorist plot by Osama bin Laden to kill thousands of Americans on their home soil, published a full year before the World Trade Center Attacks. His scenario of McGarvey tracking bin Laden to his urban lair in Pakistan and shooting him in the head\u2014far from Tora Bora\u2019s caves\u2014was described and executed in \u201cAllah\u2019s Scorpion (2007)\u201d four years before the eerily similar event echoed Hagberg\u2019s novel.\r\n\r\nLike many \"cloak-and-dagger\" novelists, Hagberg has a professional background in espionage, having spent his stint of military duty as a cryptographer for U.S. Air Force Intelligence. Hagberg apprenticed as a spy writer by contributing more than 20 \"work-for-hire\" entries in the Nick Carter - Killmaster series of espionage novels between 1976 and 1987. He also wrote \"work-for-hire\" novels based on the Flash Gordon comic strip. {"bio": "**Professor & Writer**

                                        
**Professor Nezameddin Faghih** is a Professor of Management. He received his B.Sc. (1976), M.Sc. (1977), PhD (1980) from University of Surrey (England). His main research interests are in the interdisciplinary areas and he is known as a thinker for his writings on interrelating science to many interdisciplinary fields.
Professor Faghih is the founding chief editor of the newly established journal of Global Entrepreneurship Research (an international academic Journal in English), and associate editor of ten academic journals. He is also the founding and former chief editor of the Iranian Journal of Information Science and Technology. 
He is a member of Global Entrepreneurship Monitor and holds other Professional Memberships and Fellowships. He is also a subject of Marquis Who's Who (USA) in the World, in Science and in Finance and Business; and the Asian/ American Who's Who (India).
He has won numerous awards and honors, including Distinguished Professor Award of National Excellence (2000), Distinguished Researcher Award (1999-2008), Distinguished Researcher in Fars Province Award (2000), Excellence in Research Award (1995, 1998), and Scholarly Book of the Year Author Award (1990).
Professor Faghih is the author of numerous articles and scholarly books. Professor Faghih is the author and co-author of thirty six scholarly books and over one hundred major refereed articles in a wide spectrum of scientific topics from random signal analysis, data
